There is a store, gift shop and a visitor center and the ranger/staff are very nice, friendly and helpful. There is a park $10 fee which is well worth it. <text>Beautiful park with many unique trees.  This place feels similar to Henry Cowell Redwoods State Park in many ways, but the location is slightly more remote in that you will need to traverse many more miles of winding roads to reach visitor's center.  With this remoteness comes a deeper and less crowded forest that is photogenic at every turn.  Definitely worth a visit.</text><Date>1503038041241</Date></record>

< Text>
Did the Berry Creek Trail. About 11 miles. A good long hike with a couple waterfalls on the way. Not an intense hike, just a long one. Might be better in spring rather than November (when I visited) - hike felt a little monotonous for how long it was but it's a pretty place with redwoods. Day well spent.< /Text>

< review>
Beautiful forested State Park.  I‚Äôve stayed in redwood forests before but not one the size and scope of BIg Basin.  It was a wonderful place to unplug and unwind for 6 days. Plenty of trials and scenery throughout. We stayed in the rustic Huckleberry cabins which was a nice set up, saving from having to tow or set up a tent. A hike to Berry Falls with young family members was a nice half day trek. This is a top 5 camping experience for me.</review>

<text>I've always been wary of pawn shops because I was uneducated and believed the stigma from people who were just as uneducated. I've passed by Traders for years and I finally went in to see about selling an old gold ring I had that I didn't wear.

I like this library! It's small but they have a decent selection of fiction and non-fiction books, and DVDs. The library itself is rather clean and pleasant, and the staff is helpful (if a little cranky from time to time). < review>
Nice setup since the remodel. There's plenty of machines for cardio & to workout + free weights. The sauna and hot tub are cool features but I hardly use them myself. It's a fairly big gym with an indoor basketball court. The one thing that could be improved is making sure that the paper towel dispensers are refilled more often. There's plenty of parking, although it can get busy around 5-7 pm on weekdays. Friday evening and Sunday evening is when I find the gym less full.< /review>

< Rating>

<Text>I made the mistake of taking my work vehicle to speedy oil change place to get my transmission flush since they offer the service. Worst choice ever. Long story short, after a few weeks of getting that service done my vehicle started having issues. I took it back to get it checked out and they said nothing was wrong. After still having issues with the vehicle I decided to take it to the dealer. I told them what was going on and that I had taken it to speedy to do a transmission flush and if they could check the oil level in the transmission. They also diagnosed the vehicle and ended up telling me the oil level was fine and I needed a new transmission. They gave me an estimate of $4,500 to replace my transmission. I was not convinced of their diagnosis so I wanted to get a second opinion. That's when I took it to Fred's Wrench Shop. As soon as arrived and told them the situation, Fred grabbed a dip stick and checked the oil level in the transmission. Sure enough the level was low. Fred topped it off and we went for a test drive. My vehicle was back to normal! I ended up having Fred's do the full transmission service just to have peace of mind after speedy didn't do what they were supposed to do. My transmission works better than before.
Lesson learned...never go to those quick service places like speedy. And I'm never going to trust the dealer since they tried to sell me on a new transmission when it didn't need one. I live in Brentwood but I'll be happy to drive out to Fred's Wrench Shop to have my vehicles service there in the future. I highly recommend Fred's Wrench Shop to everyone.</Text></record>

<Review>Great history in this downtown Azusa restaurant.
Plenty of great food and lots of space for dining with a big or small party. I had the combination platter myself and enjoyed all the food. I did have to take of a bit of the cheese. If you go the combination route I'd suggest asking if you can have less cheese or instead of a cheese enchilada try chicken.
They have an outdoor area which is perfect at night and as an alternative to the inside seating.
You may have a wait but the service and food are all worth it.
You may want to ask for the spicier salsa I tried it for the first time on Saturday and appreciate the extra flavor. There original salsa is a classic and great till the very last dip. If you ever need fresh tortilla chips and salsa for a party. GO HERE!!!</Review>< GmapID>

<Response>{'time': 1599755648257, 'text': "Eli, while we enjoyed welcoming you and your family in for the first time, it's disappointing to hear our flavors were anything but great. 1599583331265</Date>
<Pics>None<//Pics><Gmap_id>0x80c327eca28e22e3:0x61da8f9902c7d08d</Gmap_id><review>Passed by La Tolteca today from our trip up the mountains of Azusa.
I noticed the amount of great reviews this place had so I was expecting something great, but unfortunately I was completely let down.

My wife and I ordered three different plates in total which were an order of carnitas served with rice and beans, two shrimp tacos, and an order of chicken flautas.

Let's start with one of my favorite dishes, shrimp tacos. I don't think there has ever been a shrimp taco I've personally disliked, sadly this has to be it. The tacos came served on a really hot plate with two large corn tortillas, three normal sized shrimp, and a ton of lettuce. Yes, lettuce. Normally one would expect cabbage for shrimp tacos but not here. The ratios were very off as well. It was far too much tortilla (two tortillas per taco to be exact) and lettuce for the amount of shrimp that were given. Not only that but the shrimp itself were flavorless, and it didn't help that the tacos didn't have some kind of mayo or any kind of sauce that you'll find in any other place. At least a slice of lemon would be great to join these tacos, just to get some kind of flavor here.

Next up are the chicken flautas. The portions were quite generous with these. It's two chicken flautas with lettuce and quite an amount of guacamole a sour cream on the side. I have to admit, I was hoping for a great chicken flauta once I took the first crunchy bite but after the second one I was let down once again. Normally when it comes to chicken flautas, restaurants tend to add cheese inside the taco so it could give it some flavor but inside there was only shredded dry chicken. Actually it tasted more like tinga, but with tinga you usually get cheese on top. So no, no cheese anywhere on the chicken flautas. It didn't help that the chicken was completely dry as well.

Lastly was the plate of carnitas served with rice and beans. This one was not too bad actually. It came with tortillas but I had left over tortillas from the shrimp tacos. There not much to say about this plate. Maybe just that the rice and beans didn't taste fresh. But that's a common thing for restaurants to do. The carnitas itself were soft but some lemon, cilantro and diced onion would have been great on the side.

Overall I was expecting much more from this place. Especially from seeing all the positive reviews. I probably wont be coming back here anytime soon and that's unfortunate because I do plan to make more trips up the mountains of Azusa more often. It was a very nice first time trip for my family. Hope this place makes some drastic changes to some of our (my wife and I) favorite plates.</review>< userid>
101942292521303796597<//userid>

< review>
I've been going here since I was a kid when it was in the old building down the street. The food is always very good and authentic. The newer building is huge and beautiful inside. The perfect mix of Mexican folkloric and modern. The addition of the full bar is nice. The large screen TVs are good for watching sports, but honestly too large and slightly annoying. The only other reason I'm taking away one star is the service. Often the staff is short with their customers and snappy. I know they're busy, but being more genuine would go a long way in making people feel appreciated.< /review>
<date>1574820042734< /date>< Resp>

< Pictures>

< Text>
Great Mexican food, been coming here since before it was at this location. Their chunky guacamole is where it's at!

I'm going to add a bit more to this review:

Like I said, I've been coming here for years with my family. The food is delicious and there's something on the menu for everyone. My family is very big on the taquitos. I personally love their hard shell tacos and rice. Everyone in my family loves the tamales. The staff are all wonderful and friendly. Have never had a problem with service or food.
The atmosphere is warm and welcoming, often they have whatever sports game is on for the day/night. They have a nice bar with a succinct tap list featuring some craft brews!
Their margaritas are good as well.

It tends to be busy at night, not so busy that you can't find a table but busy enough that you're surrounded by other people that are happily enjoying their food with their families. Often times they've even had musicians playing at the restaurant.< /Text>
< resp>

<Time>1577566227504<//Time><text>Paid this restaurant a visit for breakfast hoping the name would support a true level of authenticity; we were wrong.

LOCATION:
The restaurant is centrally located in Asuza. It's a large building with a decent sized parking lot. The facility is clean and open.

STAFF:
Staff we engaged were friendly and courteous.

FOOD:
We ordered the huevos rancheros, enchiladas, huevos con chorizo and bean, cheese and egg breakfast burrito. The family consensus was that the food was missing a lot of flavor (salt, pepper, spices, etc.). Though the first red flag should have been the chips and salsa appetizer - lack luster.

VERDICT:
All in all, the cleanliness and staff professionalism weren't enough to overcome the mediocre food experience. The food was either mass produced and lost flavor or the cooks don't have the necessary experience to warrant an authentic flavor profile. We definitely will not be returning.< /text>< Gmap_id>

<gmap_id>0x80c327eca28e22e3:0x61da8f9902c7d08d<//gmap_id>< Text>
First time going. Just stopped here on our way from Crystal lake back to San Diego. Randomly choose to eat lunch here and I'm glad we did. Told the guy at the counter that it was our first time here, so he gave us a free chips and salsa AND guacamole. All of their corn products are made in house. That's why the building looks like a big movie theater. Definitely had great food too. Got the carnita burrito and a pork tamale. Very good.
Customer service was just as good as the food. Next time I'm in this town, I'll definitely stop by again.</Text>

< review>
Paid this restaurant a visit for breakfast hoping the name would support a true level of authenticity; we were wrong.

LOCATION:
The restaurant is centrally located in Asuza. It's a large building with a decent sized parking lot. The facility is clean and open.

STAFF:
Staff we engaged were friendly and courteous.

FOOD:
We ordered the huevos rancheros, enchiladas, huevos con chorizo and bean, cheese and egg breakfast burrito. The family consensus was that the food was missing a lot of flavor (salt, pepper, spices, etc.). Though the first red flag should have been the chips and salsa appetizer - lack luster.

VERDICT:
All in all, the cleanliness and staff professionalism weren't enough to overcome the mediocre food experience. The food was either mass produced and lost flavor or the cooks don't have the necessary experience to warrant an authentic flavor profile. We definitely will not be returning.<//review>

< review>
My son and daughter-in-law treated me to La Tolteca yesterday for my 1st visit. I lived it! The Santa Fe Style was well done, the food was great, it was full but the line kept moving. You are supposed to order 1st and Pay, get your number and then be seated. Of course there were disrespectful people in line who left a person to order and pay and then proceeded to pick a table/booth despite signs at the front door stating NOT to do that. Everyone seem to be having a good time. The service is great. I will be coming here as one of my favorite places. It is a great place to take the family and you don't fill rushed.<//review>

< Time>
1554698786428< /Time>
<rating>1< /rating>< text>
For a place thats been in business so long... I was very unimpressed.
The salsa was the saddest I have had in LA or anywhere.  It tasted like can tomato's and lime.  No onion, no garlic, no chillis, barely any cilantro.
I ordered the combination plate.   The enchilada was good. Rice seasoned nicely, but barely warm.  Beans ok.  The guacamole was creamy, whipped and needed salt.  And it was served on top of a salsa garnish.
The steak had zero flavor.  It was like pot roast in a taco shell.  No seasoning.. in the taquito, chill rellenao "pork maybe" and taco.
If you like flavorless food, and can't eat salts or spices this would be the place to go.  The place was nice and clean with friendly staff.
You order your food. Pay first and get a number to take to your table.  They brought the food out and not once did any server return.  It's basically a glorified cafeteria experiance.  Bland and souless.< /text>

Went here and the order taker asked if I was ready.  I said yes, stepped forward to place my order and he started talking to others. So I waited. Then when he was finished talking, he said he was ready when I was, as if I was busy thinking instead of waiting for him.  Then I placed my order, but he didn‚Äôt hear me, so I repeated it. And he said,  you want what?  I then stopped and said, maybe I should ask if you‚Äôre ready, and smiled.  He didn‚Äôt smile, but just asked, what‚Äôd I like to have. I said I‚Äôd like to get a carnitas burrito plate, but it‚Äôs not in the list, and he said don‚Äôt worry I can make that for you.  I said, wait, for how much, and he said $13 something, which is more expensive, almost like ordering a plate of something for $8.50 and a separate burrito.  So I thought I wasn‚Äôt there to get hustled, so I just asked for a beef enchilada plate. When the food came it looked great. But the beef smelt like it‚Äôd gone bad two days earlier.  I smelt it again and it reminded me of the South East Asian markets in Asia where they serve dog and cat.  It really pungent, and they spice it a lot, and when they do that you don‚Äôt taste a lot of spice, because the meatiness of dog and cat cancels out the spice. <user_id>103169820004039686844< /user_id><resp>None< /resp>< review>
I have worked two blocks from here for the past three years, today was my first experience there and my last.

I was told the burritos were pretty good, so I ordered a carnitas burritos, playing it save since carnitas are flavorful on their own, not here. The carnitas were bland and it took me eating half the burrito to actually get to them, it was a runny refried beans burrito with carnitas and guacamole. The chips were good, tasted fresh. The red salsa is just tomato salsa, and their "spicy" salsa is not actually spicy but has a good smokey flavor. I asked for a little salsa container to go for the half of the burrito I was taking home, I was told it was $1. Who charges a dine in customer for salsa for their left over food?

This place might be popular due to nostalgia in the neighborhood and city because if your carnitas have no flavor and your refried beans are runny, I'm scared to try other more complex dishes.

If you want a delicious and flavorful carnitas burrito, go to Mr. Alberto on Rte 66.</review>
